WEBVTT

1
00:01:01.095 --> 00:01:03.697
Day 42. session 72.

2
00:01:04.798 --> 00:01:06.267
Start recording.

3
00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:08.035
Vitals?

4
00:01:08.169 --> 00:01:10.104
Blood pressure 110 over 70.

5
00:01:10.238 --> 00:01:11.239
Pulse 68.

6
00:01:11.372 --> 00:01:12.673
Vitals normal.

7
00:01:12.806 --> 00:01:15.743
Dr. Kask. what did you see?

8
00:01:16.544 --> 00:01:18.011
What did they show you?

9
00:01:20.047 --> 00:01:21.382
Dr. Kask?

10
00:01:22.583 --> 00:01:24.252
Dr. Kask?

11
00:01:26.387 --> 00:01:28.055
How are you still alive?

12
00:01:49.710 --> 00:01:51.312
How am I still alive?

13
00:01:57.451 --> 00:01:58.886
We're a flawed species.

14
00:02:01.755 --> 00:02:04.625
Okay. are you ready to meet your little sister?

15
00:02:12.233 --> 00:02:14.902
We're impossibly fragile.

16
00:02:15.869 --> 00:02:17.271
Hi. Klara. Hi.

17
00:02:17.405 --> 00:02:18.539
Yeah.

18
00:02:18.672 --> 00:02:19.973
Do you think we should keep her?

19
00:02:21.475 --> 00:02:22.843
Yeah.

20
00:02:29.817 --> 00:02:31.051
We're self destructive.

21
00:02:40.894 --> 00:02:42.463
Superstitious.

22
00:02:48.902 --> 00:02:50.238
Driven by fear.

23
00:02:57.445 --> 00:02:58.812
By love.

24
00:03:03.484 --> 00:03:07.255
Barely able to survive on our tiny blue rock.

25
00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:12.893
let alone in the endless black ocean of our universe.

26
00:03:13.026 --> 00:03:14.995
Top bunk!

27
00:03:18.866 --> 00:03:20.768
What's past the last planet?

28
00:03:22.002 --> 00:03:23.271
Infinity.

29
00:03:27.007 --> 00:03:28.342
Everything.

30
00:03:29.009 --> 00:03:30.344
Anything.

31
00:03:31.245 --> 00:03:32.846
Whoa.

32
00:03:33.947 --> 00:03:35.516
Nothing ever lasts.

33
00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:38.018
How am I still alive?

34
00:03:42.656 --> 00:03:43.991
We need to let it go.

35
00:03:45.326 --> 00:03:47.060
It needs to breathe.

36
00:03:54.668 --> 00:03:57.938
One day. we will die.

37
00:04:02.142 --> 00:04:03.544
Hey. you okay?

38
00:04:05.779 --> 00:04:06.914
Mom?

39
00:04:07.047 --> 00:04:08.549
Mom! Mom!

40
00:04:10.150 --> 00:04:11.752
We become dust.

41
00:04:11.885 --> 00:04:13.487
Oh my God. what happened?

42
00:04:13.621 --> 00:04:15.255
Klara! Klara!

43
00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:20.193
And our dust

44
00:04:20.328 --> 00:04:23.564
joins all the other dust of the universe.

45
00:04:29.102 --> 00:04:30.638
And everything we love...

46
00:04:34.708 --> 00:04:35.976
Goes away.

47
00:04:40.981 --> 00:04:42.583
How am I still alive?

48
00:04:45.185 --> 00:04:47.588
How are any of us?

49
00:04:54.194 --> 00:04:57.798
What if biological life is just a stage?

50
00:04:58.265 --> 00:04:59.833
What if we can evolve?

51
00:04:59.967 --> 00:05:04.838
So our future as a species is post-biological?

52
00:05:05.573 --> 00:05:08.275
Our present is post-biological.

53
00:05:08.742 --> 00:05:12.780
It took us six thousand years to
go from leeches to pacemakers.

54
00:05:12.913 --> 00:05:13.913
But from pacemakers

55
00:05:14.014 --> 00:05:16.484
to genetically modifying human embryos.

56
00:05:16.617 --> 00:05:18.085
it took just 60.

57
00:05:18.218 --> 00:05:21.054
Mm-hmm. So this isn't the future.

58
00:05:21.221 --> 00:05:22.723
The future is right now.

59
00:05:22.856 --> 00:05:24.492
Let me ask you this though.

60
00:05:24.625 --> 00:05:27.027
if our destiny is post-biological.

61
00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:29.997
is there other life in the universe as well?

62
00:05:31.031 --> 00:05:33.401
Oh. that's a stone cold certainty.

63
00:05:34.167 --> 00:05:35.167
Okay. wait. wait.

64
00:05:35.235 --> 00:05:36.404
Here's what I want to know.

65
00:05:37.104 --> 00:05:41.108
Is there something you know that we don't?

66
00:05:41.241 --> 00:05:44.111
Look. people call me a tech visionary.

67
00:05:44.244 --> 00:05:45.846
That's just a bunch of horseshit.

68
00:05:47.481 --> 00:05:50.651
I'm just a fellow that sees what's right in front of him.

69
00:05:50.784 --> 00:05:53.320
And it ain't no secret that I made my first billion

70
00:05:53.454 --> 00:05:55.222
from solar energy.

71
00:05:55.556 --> 00:05:57.925
but I did not invent the sun.

72
00:05:58.659 --> 00:06:00.093
I'm no visionary.

73
00:06:01.529 --> 00:06:07.167
Visionaries see things that no one else does.

74
00:06:09.269 --> 00:06:10.738
and that's rare.

75
00:06:11.705 --> 00:06:14.141
Okay. so who does Sam Houston

76
00:06:14.274 --> 00:06:15.843
consider a visionary?

77
00:06:18.412 --> 00:06:19.547
Well. you know what?

78
00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:22.249
We have one right here in this very room.

79
00:06:27.488 --> 00:06:28.756
Annika Kask.

80
00:06:31.391 --> 00:06:32.392
Annika Kask.

81
00:06:32.526 --> 00:06:34.361
would you please raise your hand?

82
00:06:37.364 --> 00:06:38.866
There she is.

83
00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:44.104
The first person to photograph dark matter.

84
00:06:50.343 --> 00:06:52.179
- That's it.
- There you go.

85
00:06:52.312 --> 00:06:53.714
Fantastic. Thank you.

86
00:06:53.847 --> 00:06:55.158
- Well. you bet.
- Thank you so much.

87
00:06:55.182 --> 00:06:56.182
Thanks for having me.

88
00:06:56.249 --> 00:06:57.117
Appreciate it.

89
00:06:57.250 --> 00:06:58.251
That was really great.

90
00:06:58.385 --> 00:06:59.385
Nobody got hurt.

91
00:06:59.419 --> 00:07:00.888
Oh. uh. excuse me.

92
00:07:03.957 --> 00:07:05.225
Annika?

93
00:07:05.358 --> 00:07:06.927
- Hi.
- Hey.

94
00:07:07.294 --> 00:07:09.096
Big fan. Big fan.

95
00:07:09.563 --> 00:07:11.899
Thank you. I'm flattered.

96
00:07:12.032 --> 00:07:15.703
Well. uh. I have a confession to make.

97
00:07:16.704 --> 00:07:19.406
I didn't come here just to do a TED Talk.

98
00:07:21.308 --> 00:07:23.276
I want to offer you a job.

99
00:07:27.948 --> 00:07:29.783
You know. most people.

100
00:07:30.150 --> 00:07:33.186
they look at the universe and it's empty.

101
00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:36.990
And you. with one image. proved 'em all wrong.

102
00:07:37.958 --> 00:07:39.192
How'd you do it?

103
00:07:43.664 --> 00:07:45.533
Every time we'd try and image it.

104
00:07:45.666 --> 00:07:47.034
we'd get chaos.

105
00:07:47.801 --> 00:07:49.121
Couldn't find the right data set.

106
00:07:49.169 --> 00:07:50.203
What was the right set?

107
00:07:50.337 --> 00:07:51.337
All of them.

108
00:07:51.905 --> 00:07:53.206
At once.

109
00:07:53.340 --> 00:07:55.208
Overlapping. Like 3D glasses.

110
00:07:55.342 --> 00:07:56.877
Except instead of just red and blue.

111
00:07:57.010 --> 00:08:00.213
we overlap 233 data sets

112
00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:01.982
to find order in the chaos.

113
00:08:02.115 --> 00:08:04.618
And then you get that.

114
00:08:05.586 --> 00:08:07.320
Well. that's the how. but...

115
00:08:09.356 --> 00:08:10.691
why?

116
00:08:13.594 --> 00:08:15.663
No one's ever asked me that before.

117
00:08:19.166 --> 00:08:23.003
I guess I just want to know what's out there.

118
00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:25.138
You want to know what's out there?

119
00:08:25.272 --> 00:08:26.674
Why not down here?

120
00:08:29.810 --> 00:08:31.178
It's a one-year contract.

121
00:08:31.979 --> 00:08:36.183
Small lab on a remote island in the Caribbean.

122
00:08:36.316 --> 00:08:37.350
What lab?

123
00:08:37.484 --> 00:08:39.019
That's confidential.

124
00:08:39.987 --> 00:08:42.690
You need scientists to work on a secret project

125
00:08:42.823 --> 00:08:44.491
on a remote island in the Caribbean?

126
00:08:44.625 --> 00:08:45.859
Let me tell you something.

127
00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:48.862
There's more up there.

128
00:08:49.863 --> 00:08:51.098
and down here.

129
00:08:51.231 --> 00:08:52.099
Everywhere.

130
00:08:52.232 --> 00:08:53.400
Aliens.

131
00:08:59.973 --> 00:09:03.110
Look. Mr. Houston. I appreciate the offer.

132
00:09:03.243 --> 00:09:05.779
but I'm not the kind of scientist who hunts for aliens.

133
00:09:05.913 --> 00:09:07.514
We're not hunting.

134
00:09:08.716 --> 00:09:09.917
We're gathering.

135
00:09:11.018 --> 00:09:14.554
And we need your discovery to make sense of it.

136
00:09:15.555 --> 00:09:16.857
Look.

137
00:09:17.424 --> 00:09:19.960
you can forget about your little green men.

138
00:09:20.393 --> 00:09:22.596
fishing for radio waves.

139
00:09:22.730 --> 00:09:24.965
and hunting for a needle in a haystack.

140
00:09:25.098 --> 00:09:27.434
because I'm here to tell you that the whole haystack

141
00:09:27.567 --> 00:09:29.569
is made out of needles.

142
00:09:29.937 --> 00:09:31.772
We're not alone in the dark.

143
00:09:32.606 --> 00:09:36.944
In fact. the darkness has been our company all along.

144
00:09:39.446 --> 00:09:41.214
You want to find out?

145
00:09:57.464 --> 00:09:59.833
I am an electronics engineer.

146
00:10:00.934 --> 00:10:01.934
Charlie Kaminsky.

147
00:10:03.704 --> 00:10:05.138
Sorry. it's just...

148
00:10:05.873 --> 00:10:08.642
Charlie Kaminsky saying he's an electronics engineer

149
00:10:08.776 --> 00:10:12.279
is like Stephen Hawking saying he teaches math.

150
00:10:12.412 --> 00:10:15.983
Yeah. I'm the CTO of Gateway Labs.

151
00:10:16.583 --> 00:10:18.819
Sam hired me to check some new toys he's building.

152
00:10:18.952 --> 00:10:20.630
Now. where do you-where do you work. Annika?

153
00:10:20.654 --> 00:10:21.755
R.I.T.

154
00:10:22.622 --> 00:10:24.124
You're Annika Kask?

155
00:10:24.257 --> 00:10:25.325
Yeah. wow.

156
00:10:25.458 --> 00:10:27.160
How did. uh. how did Sam land you?

157
00:10:27.294 --> 00:10:29.629
He promised me we weren't hunting for aliens.

158
00:10:30.630 --> 00:10:31.932
You?

159
00:10:32.332 --> 00:10:33.701
He promised me we were.

160
00:10:36.804 --> 00:10:38.005
Oh. wow.

161
00:11:06.033 --> 00:11:07.400
Welcome to the island.

162
00:11:07.534 --> 00:11:08.802
Thank you.

163
00:11:08.936 --> 00:11:10.646
Uh. how many people are working out here right now?

164
00:11:10.670 --> 00:11:11.671
Nine or ten.

165
00:11:11.805 --> 00:11:13.707
Dr. Glassner likes to keep it small.

166
00:11:14.541 --> 00:11:15.642
Perry Glassner?

167
00:11:17.711 --> 00:11:19.346
Wow. Shit. Okay.

168
00:11:19.479 --> 00:11:21.915
Yeah. super friends unite. I like it.

169
00:11:22.049 --> 00:11:23.350
We'll see to your luggage.

170
00:11:23.483 --> 00:11:25.528
Dr. Glassner is waiting for you in the main facility.

171
00:11:25.552 --> 00:11:26.754
Great.

172
00:11:27.354 --> 00:11:29.990
Oh. um. I'll-I'll catch up.

173
00:11:30.123 --> 00:11:31.267
Here. just be careful with...

174
00:11:31.291 --> 00:11:32.692
Yeah. it's delicate.

175
00:11:32.826 --> 00:11:33.937
- Thank you so much.
- No problem.

176
00:11:33.961 --> 00:11:34.961
Thank you. Thank you.

177
00:11:34.995 --> 00:11:37.164
Perfect. Oh. there we go.

178
00:11:37.297 --> 00:11:38.457
You can take that one for me.

179
00:11:38.565 --> 00:11:39.733
Thanks.

180
00:12:52.205 --> 00:12:53.240
What's this?

181
00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:55.408
B12 methylphenidate.

182
00:12:55.542 --> 00:12:57.110
Immuno-booster.

183
00:13:11.091 --> 00:13:13.360
You shatter a bone and it heals.

184
00:13:13.493 --> 00:13:15.795
but you bruise trust and it's fatal.

185
00:13:18.331 --> 00:13:19.566
What's your purpose?

186
00:13:20.233 --> 00:13:21.701
I'm Dr. Annika Kask.

187
00:13:22.402 --> 00:13:24.104
Well. that's a chair I can sit in

188
00:13:24.237 --> 00:13:26.106
and that's a door I can walk out of.

189
00:13:26.239 --> 00:13:28.208
so what is your purpose?

190
00:13:29.142 --> 00:13:30.443
Sam Houston sent me.

191
00:13:30.577 --> 00:13:31.845
Why would he do that?

192
00:13:34.114 --> 00:13:35.282
I'm a computer scientist.

193
00:13:35.415 --> 00:13:37.017
Oh. right.

194
00:13:37.985 --> 00:13:39.286
That's a shame.

195
00:13:40.187 --> 00:13:41.388
That's a shame.

196
00:13:41.521 --> 00:13:43.432
I thought you might have the salt to admit the truth.

197
00:13:43.456 --> 00:13:46.659
that you've been sent here by Sam to spy on me.

198
00:13:47.694 --> 00:13:50.063
To be the bruise that kills me.

199
00:13:51.932 --> 00:13:52.932
Should I go?

200
00:13:53.033 --> 00:13:54.567
No. no. no. no. no. no.

201
00:13:55.268 --> 00:13:58.005
After all. I might need an algorithm.

202
00:13:59.306 --> 00:14:01.541
Oh. Dr. Glassner. hi. I'm Charlie.

203
00:14:01.674 --> 00:14:04.544
And I gotta tell you. man. from one scientist to another...

204
00:14:04.677 --> 00:14:07.080
Here we go. They're fucking multiplying.

205
00:14:09.950 --> 00:14:12.319
I blew it. I...

206
00:14:13.653 --> 00:14:14.687
As per your NDAs.

207
00:14:14.821 --> 00:14:16.256
communications are monitored.

208
00:14:16.389 --> 00:14:17.724
You will be watched.

209
00:14:17.857 --> 00:14:19.326
It feels like overkill.

210
00:14:19.459 --> 00:14:21.361
Yes. it's completely and utterly unnecessary.

211
00:14:21.494 --> 00:14:24.164
I should be doing this work on my own in my basement.

212
00:14:24.297 --> 00:14:27.500
but Sam would never allow that
because this isn't really a lab.

213
00:14:27.634 --> 00:14:30.203
It's a shrine to a man's overwhelming hubris.

214
00:14:30.337 --> 00:14:32.872
See. most billionaires buy yachts or football teams.

215
00:14:33.006 --> 00:14:35.742
but he wants to buy ideas or legacies to show the world

216
00:14:35.875 --> 00:14:38.345
he's somehow changed the course of human history.

217
00:14:39.146 --> 00:14:40.613
So that's what you do here?

218
00:14:43.383 --> 00:14:44.884
That's what we're about to do.

219
00:14:45.652 --> 00:14:48.288
Welcome to the Tuning Lab.

220
00:14:49.889 --> 00:14:52.725
So you. you're up to speed?

221
00:14:52.859 --> 00:14:55.762
That dark matter algorithm you discovered.

222
00:14:56.096 --> 00:14:57.730
you'll need to apply it here.

223
00:14:57.864 --> 00:14:59.699
Is this what I think it is? Does it work?

224
00:14:59.832 --> 00:15:01.969
No. Yes. And get the fuck away from it.

225
00:15:02.435 --> 00:15:03.736
- Right. Where to begin?
- Sorry.

226
00:15:03.870 --> 00:15:06.606
Let's begin at the beginning. uh. in darkness.

227
00:15:06.739 --> 00:15:10.443
So let there be light and heat and bacteria.

228
00:15:10.577 --> 00:15:11.744
single-celled organisms.

229
00:15:11.878 --> 00:15:13.480
Skip a few billion years.

230
00:15:13.613 --> 00:15:15.148
Reptiles. monkeys. then us.

231
00:15:15.282 --> 00:15:16.616
Apex predators.

232
00:15:16.749 --> 00:15:17.784
Petty. ain't we?

233
00:15:17.917 --> 00:15:19.052
Cruel.

234
00:15:19.186 --> 00:15:20.753
Prone to self-destruction.

235
00:15:20.887 --> 00:15:21.989
Hell bent on rage.

236
00:15:22.122 --> 00:15:23.923
fucking our habitat out of existence.

237
00:15:24.057 --> 00:15:25.792
So now we turn our eyes away from Earth

238
00:15:25.925 --> 00:15:27.727
in search of other worlds to defile.

239
00:15:27.860 --> 00:15:29.229
But there's a hitch.

240
00:15:29.362 --> 00:15:32.132
Because Mr. Drake's equation tells us that we're not alone.

241
00:15:32.265 --> 00:15:33.800
The universe is too vast.

242
00:15:33.933 --> 00:15:35.102
rich with resources.

243
00:15:35.235 --> 00:15:37.470
likely swimming with intelligent life.

244
00:15:37.604 --> 00:15:38.671
Competition.

245
00:15:38.805 --> 00:15:40.049
And most of that's going to be millions.

246
00:15:40.073 --> 00:15:42.775
if not billions of years ahead of us.

247
00:15:42.909 --> 00:15:45.245
So we come into this race far. far behind.

248
00:15:45.378 --> 00:15:46.689
Nevertheless. we do start looking

249
00:15:46.713 --> 00:15:49.616
with whatever crude tools are available.

250
00:15:49.749 --> 00:15:50.917
As you know. SETI.

251
00:15:51.051 --> 00:15:52.851
the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence.

252
00:15:52.919 --> 00:15:54.654
has been scanning. uh. what?

253
00:15:54.787 --> 00:15:56.656
Oh yeah. radio waves.

254
00:15:56.789 --> 00:15:58.125
That still only covers. what.

255
00:15:58.258 --> 00:15:59.959
one ten-millionth of the night sky

256
00:16:00.093 --> 00:16:02.795
using hilariously outdated technology.

257
00:16:02.929 --> 00:16:05.532
It's like taking a little bowl of water out of the ocean

258
00:16:05.665 --> 00:16:08.135
and peering in and concluding that whales don't exist.

259
00:16:08.268 --> 00:16:09.436
No. not radio.

260
00:16:09.569 --> 00:16:11.104
That's not how you'd communicate

261
00:16:11.238 --> 00:16:13.640
if you're an interplanetary intelligence. is it?

262
00:16:13.773 --> 00:16:16.976
You want to talk across space and time instantaneously.

263
00:16:17.110 --> 00:16:18.111
So let's do this.

264
00:16:18.245 --> 00:16:20.713
Take two photons. pair them. keep one here.

265
00:16:20.847 --> 00:16:22.649
send the other light years away.

266
00:16:22.782 --> 00:16:24.684
Force one photon into a declared state.

267
00:16:24.817 --> 00:16:26.986
and the other responds in the very same moment

268
00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:28.955
across space and time.

269
00:16:29.089 --> 00:16:30.649
String a few billion of those together.

270
00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:32.825
and you've got an FTL communicator.

271
00:16:32.959 --> 00:16:35.628
No. but-but the quantum communication can't work.

272
00:16:35.762 --> 00:16:36.872
It breaks the laws of physics.

273
00:16:36.896 --> 00:16:39.332
No. no. it bends the laws that we know.

274
00:16:39.466 --> 00:16:40.733
and that's not what this is.

275
00:16:40.867 --> 00:16:42.902
No. if you force a quantum state change.

276
00:16:43.036 --> 00:16:44.271
that breaks entanglement...

277
00:16:44.404 --> 00:16:46.306
This machine does not force a state change!

278
00:16:46.439 --> 00:16:48.575
It doesn't entangle or disentangle.

279
00:16:48.708 --> 00:16:50.243
It just hears when someone has.

280
00:16:50.377 --> 00:16:52.579
This simply listens.

281
00:16:52.712 --> 00:16:54.013
It's impossible.

282
00:16:54.147 --> 00:16:56.716
And yet here we have a machine that does exactly that.

283
00:16:56.849 --> 00:16:59.719
that I built six years ago in my basement.

284
00:16:59.852 --> 00:17:01.754
on my own on amphetamines.

285
00:17:01.888 --> 00:17:03.890
So. take a look for yourself.

286
00:17:05.292 --> 00:17:06.826
What do you want us to do?

287
00:17:07.627 --> 00:17:08.828
Well. here's a hint.

288
00:17:09.028 --> 00:17:10.730
You've already done it.

289
00:17:14.834 --> 00:17:17.370
It says he's scanning the radius of a couple of feet.

290
00:17:17.504 --> 00:17:18.571
Right here.

291
00:17:18.705 --> 00:17:21.241
So if he's listening for aliens. then it's...

292
00:17:21.374 --> 00:17:22.375
He's doing it right here.

293
00:17:22.509 --> 00:17:23.676
in this-in this room.

294
00:17:24.043 --> 00:17:25.988
But-but what is it? I mean. like these are just...

295
00:17:26.012 --> 00:17:27.547
It's... It's a ton of data points.

296
00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:29.682
It's-it's-it's like background noise

297
00:17:29.816 --> 00:17:30.936
of anywhere in the universe.

298
00:17:31.017 --> 00:17:32.661
There's no rhyme or reason behind it. It's...

299
00:17:32.685 --> 00:17:33.685
It's chaos.

300
00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:34.721
Yeah.

301
00:17:39.926 --> 00:17:42.028
Then we find order in the chaos.

302
00:17:54.274 --> 00:17:55.908
Sort by data sets.

303
00:17:59.379 --> 00:18:00.380
Okay.

304
00:18:01.914 --> 00:18:03.716
It's the same algorithm.

305
00:18:05.785 --> 00:18:07.220
It's my algorithm.

306
00:18:09.856 --> 00:18:13.092
Sort by exponents.

307
00:18:13.926 --> 00:18:15.495
It's organizing.

308
00:18:18.198 --> 00:18:20.099
Sort by primes.

309
00:18:21.301 --> 00:18:23.570
What? W-What is this?

310
00:18:24.471 --> 00:18:25.672
I can't believe this.

311
00:18:27.607 --> 00:18:29.676
Overlay all.

312
00:18:34.113 --> 00:18:35.815
It's-it's a signal.

313
00:18:38.251 --> 00:18:40.187
They're talking.

314
00:18:48.461 --> 00:18:49.496
Holy shit!

315
00:18:52.332 --> 00:18:53.766
Dr. Glassner?

316
00:18:57.504 --> 00:18:58.871
Dr. Glassner!

317
00:18:59.005 --> 00:19:00.873
He's only scanning one little area.

318
00:19:01.007 --> 00:19:02.251
But if it's quantum communication.

319
00:19:02.275 --> 00:19:03.319
then it-it's all around us.

320
00:19:03.343 --> 00:19:04.844
Or there's another explanation.

321
00:19:04.977 --> 00:19:06.322
Or another phenomenon that we're not seeing. or...

322
00:19:06.346 --> 00:19:08.848
Or. Annika. it's fuck-to-the-yes aliens.

323
00:19:08.981 --> 00:19:10.317
- Dr. Glassner.
- I mean.

324
00:19:10.450 --> 00:19:11.960
we've been looking millions of light years away

325
00:19:11.984 --> 00:19:12.985
for-for smoke signals.

326
00:19:13.119 --> 00:19:14.297
but they were around us the entire time.

327
00:19:14.321 --> 00:19:15.888
It's...

328
00:19:16.022 --> 00:19:16.889
Is this real?

329
00:19:17.023 --> 00:19:17.890
You tell me.

330
00:19:18.024 --> 00:19:19.659
You're here to check my math.

331
00:19:19.792 --> 00:19:21.694
I mean. this means...

332
00:19:21.828 --> 00:19:22.862
It means we're not alone.

333
00:19:22.995 --> 00:19:24.531
we're not the center of the universe.

334
00:19:24.664 --> 00:19:25.798
we're not special.

335
00:19:25.932 --> 00:19:27.276
It means they don't know anything about us.

336
00:19:27.300 --> 00:19:28.535
or they don't give a fuck.

337
00:19:28.668 --> 00:19:29.668
What are they saying?

338
00:19:29.702 --> 00:19:31.037
How could I possibly know?

339
00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:33.039
We'd have to ask them with that.

340
00:19:34.274 --> 00:19:35.308
What is that?

341
00:19:35.975 --> 00:19:36.975
Littlemouth.

342
00:19:37.043 --> 00:19:38.378
You're talking to them?

343
00:19:38.511 --> 00:19:39.646
Not yet.

344
00:19:39.779 --> 00:19:40.947
You actually...

345
00:19:41.080 --> 00:19:42.591
you-you built a quantum communication device.

346
00:19:42.615 --> 00:19:43.883
Can we-can we talk back?

347
00:19:44.016 --> 00:19:46.886
No. The hardware can't replicate quantum signatures.

348
00:19:47.019 --> 00:19:48.921
I can. I've already done it in my lab.

349
00:19:49.055 --> 00:19:50.557
I highly doubt it. but...

350
00:19:54.193 --> 00:19:56.162
I suppose we're gonna find out.

351
00:19:59.966 --> 00:20:01.401
Okay. I need to...

352
00:20:03.069 --> 00:20:04.771
Oh. Oh. wow.

353
00:20:15.648 --> 00:20:17.116
Ah.

354
00:21:13.873 --> 00:21:14.974
Good morning.

355
00:21:27.253 --> 00:21:29.155
Go to the ant. consider her ways.

356
00:21:29.288 --> 00:21:30.523
and be wise.

357
00:21:30.823 --> 00:21:32.091
Do you know that?

358
00:21:34.160 --> 00:21:35.462
Hmm.

359
00:21:39.899 --> 00:21:41.634
We learn a lot from ants.

360
00:21:45.004 --> 00:21:46.439
For example. we. uh.

361
00:21:48.441 --> 00:21:51.611
we study them to. uh. solve traffic problems.

362
00:21:54.847 --> 00:21:56.282
All sorts of things.

363
00:22:03.423 --> 00:22:05.792
I hear your schooling's going well.

364
00:22:09.429 --> 00:22:10.730
I guess so.

365
00:22:15.301 --> 00:22:16.869
Good. Right.

366
00:22:54.306 --> 00:22:55.708
It's real.

367
00:23:03.416 --> 00:23:06.453
Shh. Do you hear that?

368
00:23:07.654 --> 00:23:09.088
Scared?

369
00:23:09.756 --> 00:23:11.057
No.

370
00:23:12.892 --> 00:23:14.026
Yeah.

371
00:23:17.830 --> 00:23:20.433
Mom says there's no such thing as monsters.

372
00:23:25.237 --> 00:23:26.305
I'll go check it out.

373
00:23:26.439 --> 00:23:27.707
No!

374
00:23:29.408 --> 00:23:32.111
I can't lose you.

375
00:23:49.295 --> 00:23:51.397
So this is the transmitter.

376
00:23:52.298 --> 00:23:54.467
You can't turn it on for him.

377
00:23:55.702 --> 00:23:57.269
We don't know enough yet.

378
00:23:58.471 --> 00:23:59.672
I don't know.

379
00:23:59.806 --> 00:24:01.307
How else are we going to find out?

380
00:24:02.709 --> 00:24:05.645
You're not worried what they may be capable of?

381
00:24:08.915 --> 00:24:11.150
Are you inviting me to speculate about aliens?

382
00:24:11.283 --> 00:24:13.786
Because people often regret that.

383
00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:14.921
Yeah. I am.

384
00:24:15.054 --> 00:24:16.489
- Yeah?
- Mm-hmm.

385
00:24:17.056 --> 00:24:20.159
Okay. So. the coolest project that I ever worked on.

386
00:24:20.292 --> 00:24:21.360
called the Argus 2.

387
00:24:21.494 --> 00:24:22.871
it's this bionic eye that. like this machine

388
00:24:22.895 --> 00:24:24.707
that could send microelectrodes from the optic nerve

389
00:24:24.731 --> 00:24:26.933
to the brain and then. praise Jesus.

390
00:24:27.066 --> 00:24:28.334
the blind doth see.

391
00:24:28.467 --> 00:24:30.547
And just keeps getting better and better and better.

392
00:24:30.670 --> 00:24:32.338
They get the software update every year.

393
00:24:32.471 --> 00:24:34.273
and every two years. a hardware update.

394
00:24:35.074 --> 00:24:36.175
Have you ever seen

395
00:24:36.308 --> 00:24:38.511
a three-year-old see for the first time?

396
00:24:38.978 --> 00:24:39.812
No?

397
00:24:39.946 --> 00:24:42.649
It's-it's-it's everything.

398
00:24:43.249 --> 00:24:44.617
Anyways. next year.

399
00:24:44.751 --> 00:24:46.853
the Argus 5 is going to offer better vision

400
00:24:46.986 --> 00:24:49.656
than the perfectly healthy biological eye.

401
00:24:50.356 --> 00:24:52.559
It's-it's crazy. but why stop there?

402
00:24:52.692 --> 00:24:54.970
What about all the spectrums of
light that we can't even see?

403
00:24:54.994 --> 00:24:56.062
Ultraviolet spectrum.

404
00:24:56.195 --> 00:24:57.564
the X-ray vision even.

405
00:24:57.697 --> 00:24:59.165
or thermal. whatever.

406
00:25:00.132 --> 00:25:01.467
That's just the beginning.

407
00:25:01.968 --> 00:25:03.235
We start with the eyes.

408
00:25:03.369 --> 00:25:05.705
and then we're going to move on and

409
00:25:05.838 --> 00:25:07.740
improve limbs beyond nature.

410
00:25:08.641 --> 00:25:11.210
improve livers beyond nature. the heart beyond nature.

411
00:25:11.711 --> 00:25:15.648
and eventually pass the Rubicon to the brain.

412
00:25:16.315 --> 00:25:18.651
We're going to take all of our thoughts.

413
00:25:18.785 --> 00:25:20.625
all of our reasoning. all of our intelligence.

414
00:25:20.720 --> 00:25:22.698
and we're going to put it into a more durable container.

415
00:25:22.722 --> 00:25:24.490
Could be cloud-based or silicon chip.

416
00:25:24.624 --> 00:25:25.792
something that's unbreakable.

417
00:25:25.925 --> 00:25:27.725
that can exist inside of a black hole on the.

418
00:25:27.827 --> 00:25:31.263
on the tip of a pin or in the spaces in between.

419
00:25:31.798 --> 00:25:33.032
And that...

420
00:25:33.299 --> 00:25:35.702
that is the end game for homo sapiens.

421
00:25:36.402 --> 00:25:41.240
And I think that this is just another version of us

422
00:25:41.674 --> 00:25:42.942
further down the road.

423
00:25:43.342 --> 00:25:44.811
Okay. but what about pain?

424
00:25:45.377 --> 00:25:46.879
Sorrow? Heartache?

425
00:25:47.647 --> 00:25:49.015
Profound loss?

426
00:25:49.916 --> 00:25:51.283
Regrets?

427
00:25:51.984 --> 00:25:53.019
What about 'em?

428
00:25:53.419 --> 00:25:55.121
Why-why would eliminating that be bad?

429
00:25:55.421 --> 00:25:57.056
Because they shape who we are as people.

430
00:25:57.189 --> 00:25:58.958
I think way more than pleasures do.

431
00:25:59.091 --> 00:26:03.029
I mean. so much of who I am and what I value came from.

432
00:26:03.930 --> 00:26:05.331
you know. painful experiences

433
00:26:05.464 --> 00:26:08.434
that happened in my life that I had to grow and learn from.

434
00:26:08.567 --> 00:26:09.769
And change.

435
00:26:10.569 --> 00:26:11.569
I get that.

436
00:26:11.671 --> 00:26:14.040
but human suffering as a whole. gone.

437
00:26:14.173 --> 00:26:15.574
- Can you see it?
- Yes. I see that.

438
00:26:15.708 --> 00:26:17.610
But I also see a sterile intelligence

439
00:26:17.744 --> 00:26:19.478
on a path with no interruptions.

440
00:26:19.846 --> 00:26:23.449
No purpose except to spread. with no actual growth.

441
00:26:24.116 --> 00:26:25.918
And that. to me. is not evolution.

442
00:26:26.052 --> 00:26:28.420
That is just an equation.

443
00:26:31.423 --> 00:26:34.794
And as awesome as your bionic eye sounds. Charlie.

444
00:26:35.294 --> 00:26:38.064
I actually know a lot of those
patients have had them removed.

445
00:26:38.564 --> 00:26:39.398
Some.

446
00:26:39.531 --> 00:26:40.900
And some people are weird.

447
00:26:41.033 --> 00:26:44.937
And some people value other
things in scientific perfection.

448
00:26:45.071 --> 00:26:47.339
Some people accept the parts of them

449
00:26:47.473 --> 00:26:50.442
that other people might see as imperfect.

450
00:26:51.243 --> 00:26:52.444
Hmm.

451
00:26:53.579 --> 00:26:56.849
So. we are our flaws?

452
00:26:57.950 --> 00:26:59.451
And our mistakes.

453
00:27:03.823 --> 00:27:05.091
Dr. Kask.

454
00:27:05.892 --> 00:27:08.127
you saw how unbalanced Glassner was.

455
00:27:08.260 --> 00:27:10.496
You saw the threat he posed.

456
00:27:10.763 --> 00:27:12.331
Why did you choose to stay?

457
00:27:13.499 --> 00:27:14.667
To help.

458
00:27:16.769 --> 00:27:18.771
First contact was possible.

459
00:27:20.907 --> 00:27:23.209
Would you leave it to an unbalanced nihilist

460
00:27:23.342 --> 00:27:24.944
to handle the introduction?

461
00:27:26.178 --> 00:27:27.579
This thought experiment

462
00:27:27.714 --> 00:27:31.050
dictates that the female rabbits
always give birth to pairs.

463
00:27:31.183 --> 00:27:34.386
And each pair consists of one male and one female.

464
00:27:34.520 --> 00:27:38.524
Rabbits can't reproduce until
they are at least one month old.

465
00:27:38.657 --> 00:27:40.893
She says she's very bright.

466
00:27:41.928 --> 00:27:43.562
At the end of the second month.

467
00:27:43.696 --> 00:27:45.564
- the female...
- Lucky for her.

468
00:27:47.166 --> 00:27:48.835
When month three rolls around.

469
00:27:48.968 --> 00:27:50.502
the original pair of rabbits

470
00:27:50.636 --> 00:27:53.005
produces yet another pair of newborns

471
00:27:53.139 --> 00:27:55.507
while their earlier offspring grow to adulthood.

472
00:27:55.641 --> 00:27:57.409
This leaves three pairs of rabbits.

473
00:27:57.543 --> 00:27:59.511
The order goes as follows:

474
00:27:59.645 --> 00:28:04.984
1. 1. 2. 3. 5. 8. 13. 21.

475
00:28:37.583 --> 00:28:39.218
So. is Perry your husband?

476
00:28:39.585 --> 00:28:41.187
No. I'm a doctor.

477
00:28:41.320 --> 00:28:42.388
That's his daughter.

478
00:28:45.057 --> 00:28:46.392
How long have you been here?

479
00:28:46.658 --> 00:28:48.460
I haven't left the island in three years.

480
00:28:48.594 --> 00:28:50.096
but it feels like 30.

481
00:28:53.032 --> 00:28:54.700
I don't know how you stay sane.

482
00:28:54.834 --> 00:28:56.435
What makes you think I have?

483
00:29:02.574 --> 00:29:03.910
Is he always so...

484
00:29:12.451 --> 00:29:14.821
Look. I'm not making an excuse for him.

485
00:29:16.055 --> 00:29:17.790
because there's-there's none.

486
00:29:20.059 --> 00:29:22.594
He lost his wife and son four years ago.

487
00:29:22.728 --> 00:29:24.130
and it was bad.

488
00:29:28.134 --> 00:29:30.569
He never really accepted what happened.

489
00:29:31.270 --> 00:29:32.671
What did happen?

490
00:29:33.205 --> 00:29:34.406
Well.

491
00:29:35.474 --> 00:29:37.109
there was a house fire.

492
00:29:37.643 --> 00:29:41.147
He was in his lab in an outbuilding 50 feet away.

493
00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:43.749
self medicated. probably drunk.

494
00:29:45.117 --> 00:29:48.120
Lucy? She was at a sleepover.

495
00:29:49.956 --> 00:29:51.623
But his wife and son...

496
00:29:52.558 --> 00:29:55.194
Welcome to Littlemouth's signal room.

497
00:29:55.327 --> 00:29:57.596
Perry wasn't even aware there was a fire

498
00:29:57.729 --> 00:29:59.298
until the police woke him up.

499
00:30:02.668 --> 00:30:04.503
Is he dangerous?

500
00:30:07.273 --> 00:30:09.541
He knows humans matter in theory.

501
00:30:10.910 --> 00:30:12.778
but not in practice.

502
00:30:16.782 --> 00:30:18.384
Just ask Lucy.

503
00:30:47.679 --> 00:30:49.381
Thank you.

504
00:30:52.018 --> 00:30:55.922
Lucy. I want you to watch this.

505
00:30:56.188 --> 00:30:58.757
This is a little piece of forbidden magic

506
00:30:58.891 --> 00:31:02.428
that I learned in the bazaars of Morocco

507
00:31:02.561 --> 00:31:07.866
from wise men who knew how to turn steel into thin air.

508
00:31:08.534 --> 00:31:11.503
So. I want you to count to three.

509
00:31:11.637 --> 00:31:13.705
then I want you to blow on the napkin.

510
00:31:13.839 --> 00:31:17.309
Okay. One. two. three.

511
00:31:20.412 --> 00:31:21.572
Wait. wait. wait. Let me see.

512
00:31:21.647 --> 00:31:22.748
How'd you do that? Wait.

513
00:31:22.881 --> 00:31:24.083
Go to bed.

514
00:31:29.755 --> 00:31:32.058
- Here. let me help.
- You got school in the morning.

515
00:31:32.191 --> 00:31:33.759
- Go to bed.
- Thank you.

516
00:31:34.360 --> 00:31:35.727
Good night. sweetheart.

517
00:31:36.862 --> 00:31:37.930
Good night.

518
00:31:38.730 --> 00:31:39.966
Good night. Lucy.

519
00:31:44.536 --> 00:31:45.938
You didn't eat much.

520
00:31:48.407 --> 00:31:50.642
I-I've never had goat before.

521
00:31:51.777 --> 00:31:54.780
Okay. First impressions?

522
00:31:55.714 --> 00:31:57.316
Yeah. right.

523
00:31:57.449 --> 00:32:01.320
Uh. well. I think it's completely legit.

524
00:32:01.453 --> 00:32:03.755
I mean. I've gone through six months of his logs.

525
00:32:03.889 --> 00:32:04.991
and every single time

526
00:32:05.124 --> 00:32:06.534
I tried to find some other explanation for it.

527
00:32:06.558 --> 00:32:07.926
he'd already disproved it.

528
00:32:08.060 --> 00:32:10.462
I mean. we're witnessing actual alien chatter.

529
00:32:10.596 --> 00:32:11.964
We need to report this.

530
00:32:12.298 --> 00:32:13.832
What? To who?

531
00:32:13.966 --> 00:32:15.801
The IAA has guidelines on post-detection.

532
00:32:15.934 --> 00:32:18.770
Do you want to have about a dozen space agencies

533
00:32:18.904 --> 00:32:20.772
with all the bureaucrats down here

534
00:32:20.906 --> 00:32:23.275
cluster fucking this thing for the next decade?

535
00:32:23.409 --> 00:32:25.011
I mean. Sam. I totally get it.

536
00:32:25.144 --> 00:32:26.012
and you're not wrong.

537
00:32:26.145 --> 00:32:27.779
However. Annika has a point.

538
00:32:27.913 --> 00:32:29.648
I mean. we're not fucking around anymore.

539
00:32:29.781 --> 00:32:32.318
This is like a solid seven on the RIO scale.

540
00:32:32.451 --> 00:32:34.153
Oh. for Christ sakes. Charlie.

541
00:32:34.286 --> 00:32:36.455
- You built quantum satellites.
- What?

542
00:32:36.588 --> 00:32:38.124
I thought you of all people

543
00:32:38.257 --> 00:32:39.817
would just want to run with this thing.

544
00:32:39.925 --> 00:32:40.759
I-I do.

545
00:32:40.892 --> 00:32:42.194
Look. we discovered it.

546
00:32:42.894 --> 00:32:44.096
It's ours.

547
00:32:44.230 --> 00:32:45.364
Come on. that's fucked up.

548
00:32:45.497 --> 00:32:47.333
I mean. what if-if I discovered Pluto

549
00:32:47.466 --> 00:32:49.186
I can just screw with it any way I want to?

550
00:32:49.801 --> 00:32:51.779
Billionaires. they've taken over space exploration

551
00:32:51.803 --> 00:32:54.106
because they have more resources than entire nations.

552
00:32:54.240 --> 00:32:55.641
And I'm not exactly A-OK

553
00:32:55.774 --> 00:32:57.843
with some galactic dick measuring contest

554
00:32:57.976 --> 00:32:59.778
where a few billionaires get to determine

555
00:32:59.911 --> 00:33:01.447
the fate of all of humanity.

556
00:33:01.580 --> 00:33:04.816
Sam. listening is one thing. but talking back?

557
00:33:05.817 --> 00:33:07.819
The risks of that are mind-boggling.

558
00:33:08.820 --> 00:33:11.723
We don't know if they're peaceful or hostile.

559
00:33:11.857 --> 00:33:12.858
And you're talking about

560
00:33:12.991 --> 00:33:15.561
sending a signal the way they do.

561
00:33:15.694 --> 00:33:19.665
They'll know we're here immediately from anywhere.

562
00:33:19.798 --> 00:33:22.234
You didn't say if you liked it.

563
00:33:25.003 --> 00:33:26.338
The goat.

564
00:33:29.041 --> 00:33:31.810
Yeah. uh. it was fine.

565
00:33:32.478 --> 00:33:35.481
Now. we've spent six months trying to decipher it

566
